<DOC><DOCNO> AP890111-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-11-89 1450EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w BC-CongressionalPay 1stLd-Writethru a0567 01-11 0146</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Congressional Pay, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0567,130</SECOND><HEAD>With Congressional Perks</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf to include month raise took place</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan has recommended raisingcongressional pay for rank-and-file lawmakers from $89,500 to$135,000. Here is the recent history on congressional pay.   1980 _ House and Senate members were paid $60,662 per year.   1982 _ House members $69,800 with outside earned income limitedto 30 percent of salary; Senate $60,662.   1983 _ Senate $69,800 with unlimited outside income. Houseremained unchanged.   1984 _ House and Senate, $72,000; Senate members subject to 30percent limit on outside earned income.   1985 _ House and Senate $75,100; Senate raises limit on outsideincome to 40 percent of salary.   1987 _ House and Senate, $77,400 in January; automatic increasepreviously voted.   1987 _ House and Senate, $89,500 in February; House refused toblock a Reagan pay-raise recommendation.</TEXT></DOC>